        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our sensitivity is driven by the known brightness of HD 181327 and the resolution required. Given the spectral slope, Band 7 is more sensitive for fixed observing time than Band 6 so we use Band 7. HD 181327 is 50mJy at 850um (Nilsson et al 2009), a model with the extent of the scattered light FWHM has a fairly uniform peak brightness of 0.6mJy/beam, which is a minimal estimate of the surface brightness. To ensure a robust detection we require a S/N of 20 per beam giving a noise requirement of 0.03mJy/beam (43min on source, 1.4h including overheads). CASA simulations of these observations are shown in Fig. 3 in the proposal.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>For our goal of gas detection we split one baseband into 0.847km/s channels center it on the 12CO J=3-2 line. This configuration is sufficient to resolve the ~5km/s velocity width and retain maximum bandwidth for maximum continuum sensitivity.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To ensure we resolve the HD 181327 ring sufficiently well to distinguish between the different scenarios we require an angular resolution of 0.15" (e.g. Fig. 2 in proposal). This requirement drives the sensitivity calculation.  The the ring is expected to be narrow (&lt;1"), so the largest scale we need to recover is very small and has been set to 1".
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
