        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our sensitivity is driven by the known brightness of HR 4796A, the detection of the brightness asymmetry, and the resolution required. Given the spectral slope, Band 7 is more sensitive for fixed observing time than Band 6 so we use Band 7. HR 4796A is 20mJy at 850um (Sheret et al 2004, Nilsson et al 2010), a model with the extent of the scattered light FWHM has peak brightness of 1.3mJy/beam, but is 0.6mJy/beam away from the disk ansae. With a S/N noise criterion of 20 the required noise is 0.03mJy/beam (50min on source, 1.5h including overheads). HR 4796A is known to have a mid-IR brightness asymmetry and an offset seen in scattered light. While our observations cannot detect this offset directly, it causes a 10K temperature difference between the NE and SW disk ansae (Moerchen et al 2010), corresponding to a 10% difference in sub-mm brightness. To detect this brightness difference with a confidence of 5sigma requires measuring the relative brightness of each ansa to 2% or better, or a S/N of 50. The disk ansae are 1.3mJy/beam (and in the narrow ring case 2.0mJy/beam, but of course the total flux is the same in both cases). Because the ansae are resolved a S/N of &gt;100 can be easily reached by making the flux measurement over &gt;2 resolution elements.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>For our goal of gas detection we split one baseband into 0.847km/s channels center it on the 12CO J=3-2 line. This configuration is sufficient to resolve the ~12km/s velocity width and retain maximum bandwidth for maximum continuum sensitivity.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To ensure we resolve the HR 4796A ring sufficiently well to distinguish between the different scenarios we require an angular resolution of 0.15" (e.g. Fig. 2 in proposal). This requirement drives the sensitivity calculation. The the ring is expected to be narrow (&lt;1"), so the largest scale we need to recover is very small and has been set to 1".
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
